b'Black creativity can\xe2\x80\x99t be painted in a single stroke, and the work that it inspires represents a spectrum of backgrounds, disciplines, and stories. Meet some of the artists from our "When I See Black" film:

"I wanna be able to own my narrative" - @temi.coker. Since moving from Nigeria to the US, the multidisciplinary artist has been on a creative quest to do just that. Through his Poster a Day series, he showcases a dedication to celebrating Blackness.

In questioning why there was no one who looked like her in the shows she watched growing up, artist @4everestherr shaped her mission to help portray and promote the power of the "everyday Black girl" through her gorgeous and glossy illustration style. 

Gabonese photographer @yannisdavy creates a technicolor world through his African Futurist work. Inspired by his matriarchal upbringing, he dreams for a bigger and better future. 

Check out the link in our bio to watch the full film and meet the artists.'

b'Our #WomenCreateWednesday feature @jordananncraig on #NativeAmericanHeritageMonth: "Recognizing that Indigenous peoples are existing and thriving today is imperative to Native peoples\' futures. I am also seeing more and more people, brands, and institutions acknowledging the Native land in which they reside, and this is great progress as well. \n\nWhen people want to learn more about someone\'s culture, I recommend first doing research to educate yourself on the cultural background and history before expecting a Native person to explain everything to you. If you have access to the internet or books, use these tools and learn as much as you can. Therefore, when you do talk to a Native person, you can engage in a conversation to deepen your learning and understanding."'
b'Here for the tea. :teacup_without_handle: @kzgabriella sketches out charming characters from an eye-catching perspective.'

b'Black creativity can\xe2\x80\x99t be painted in a single stroke, and the work that it inspires represents a spectrum of backgrounds, disciplines, and stories. Meet some of the artists from our "When I See Black" film:

Filmmaker and photographer @JoshuaKissi was inspired to become a storyteller while looking at his parents' photo albums of their life in Ghana. The importance of telling the most authentic version of a story has driven him to a space of immense creative flexibility. 

Fashion brand @neoncowboys was born out of @asia.hall's own experience of being a Black Chinese country fan. Her neon-hued reimagining of Americana propels a greater legacy of Black art. 

When artist @devinwesleyy sees Black, he sees \xe2\x80\x9cthat Black girls can fly.\xe2\x80\x9d His series of portraits reframe the American comic book superhero through a black lens, creating a wider and more inclusive representation. 

Check out the link in our bio to watch the full film and meet the artists.'

b'The stories, voices, and votes of women are important. @stephaniechinnart created this piece to mark the 100th anniversary of the 19th Amendment in the United States. \xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
"Creativity has always played a pivotal role in social justice movements. Through art, we can see ourselves reflected through images that tell a part of our stories and that is true for now, and it has been true throughout history. That is the reason why I balance a marriage between activism and craft in my illustrations. \xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
During the Womxn\xe2\x80\x99s suffrage movement 100 years ago, womxn were creating campaigns to support a womxn's right to vote. Female artists during the time used visual imagery to amplify their voices and to help womxn feel seen and heard through their imagery. While this was a step in the right direction, it was just the beginning in the fight for womxn\xe2\x80\x99s suffrage.\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
Today, 100 years later - visually imagery is still used help people feel seen and heard. It is still a huge important role for social justice campaigns, and it reminds us all that we have a voice and our voice matters." - @stephaniechinnart'

b'Artist and activist @shirien.creates credits her unique perspective to growing up in a family of Palestinian refugees. Read below for her experiences and insight. \xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cEarly on, I had a sense of what injustice and racism looked like through my own family\xe2\x80\x99s experience and intergenerational trauma. As I grew older, I started understanding how structural oppression functions and who it targets. I took my knowledge and put it into actively challenging these systems of oppression through community organizing and my art.\xe2\x81\xa3
My experiences helped me see the interconnectedness between the struggles of many different marginalized communities, whether it\xe2\x80\x99s Black, Palestinian, Indigenous, etc. While each struggle is unique, I learned that we don\xe2\x80\x99t face oppression within our own bubbles -- it\xe2\x80\x99s systemic and touches us all to varying degrees. \xe2\x81\xa3
My art reflects my commitment to healing, community care, and supporting and standing together with other marginalized communities. We will not be free until we are all free.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
Head to our WCW Story Highlight for more from Shirien. :dizzy:'

b'"I\xe2\x80\x99m Hannah Daisy, I\xe2\x80\x99m an illustrator and mental health occupational therapist based in London UK and I am queer. Pride to me means looking back at LGBTQAI+ history, knowing how people fought for our rights. It\xe2\x80\x99s also looking forwards, knowing there are LGBTQAI+ people who will be our future, young people right now who are out or questioning. \xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
Pride is also looking at what is happening now around the world. We have many rights here in the UK, we are covered by discrimination based on our gender, gender identity and sexuality, yet in 70 countries in the world it is illegal to be gay, some punishable by death. In others it may be technically legal but it may still be dangerous. This drawing is based on all of this, looking back, looking forwards but also what is happening right now; 'queer people anywhere are responsible for queer people everywhere' (quote by @adameli ). The idea being that in the drawing, we are connecting with others everywhere with their voices also being seen, but because of coronavirus it has to be digitally and we all come together to protest for LGBTQAI+ rights and those more privileged within our community step up, 'no one of us can be free until everybody is free\xe2\x80\x99 (Maya Angelou).\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
- @makedaisychains, illustrator and disability rights advocate. Hear more from Hannah in Pride Story Highlight.'

b'The resilience of people and the power of community inspire Blair Imani, as she uses her voice and graphic design to speak up for the marginalized. As a Black, bisexual Muslim, Blair uses creativity as a way to bring more people into the conversation and celebrate her identity. \xe2\x81\xa3\n\xe2\x81\xa3\nDon\xe2\x80\x99t miss more from @blairimani in our Women Create Wednesday Story Highlight!'
b'\xe2\x80\x9cChoose kindness, be yourself, lift each other up. :red_heart_selector: \xe2\x80\x9d - @kimsielbeck'

b"Photographer, graphic designer, and former Adobe Creative Resident @temi.coker shares the inspiration for his piece: \n\n\xe2\x80\x9cI was born and raised in Lagos, Nigeria and I vividly remember people using bleaching cream to make their skin lighter because they thought their skin was a barrier to their success. I began to think I needed lighter skin to be successful and that caused me to hate my skin color or feel like I was 'too dark'. When I came to America in 2004, something clicked in my brain and I realized that my skin was never an issue or a barrier to me being successful and seen. As I began my creative journey in photography and design I wanted to make sure that my work reflected the beauty in our skin. I have made it my life long goal and purpose to continue to show others how beautiful our skin is and remind myself that black is beautiful. That's what brought this piece to life.\xe2\x80\x9d :red_heart_selector:"
b'Embracing your truest self with acceptance and positivity \xe2\x80\x94 that\xe2\x80\x99s what @hellomynameiswednesday encourages in their work. Hear from Wednesday in our Pride Story Highlight.'

b'Her images are optimistic, vibrant, and full of life \xe2\x80\x93 just like the artist herself. @ashlukadraws shares some of her favorite pieces and her thoughts on the power of creativity to inspire change in perspectives and progress for the LGBTQIA+ community. \xe2\x81\xa3\n\xe2\x81\xa3\nDon\xe2\x80\x99t miss more from Ashley in our Women Create Wednesday Story Highlight!'

b'"For the first time I\'ve experienced a shift in the importance and significance of being a Black queer creative. Pride for me, is a time of rejoicing in my truth, in my Blackness\xe2\x80\x93 my experiences are what shaped who I am. Documenting these protests for the importance of Black lives, all Black lives, has been tremendously gripping. Documenting what\'s happening through a Black man\'s lens, you see things in a different light. It\'s so important, now more than ever, to amplify Black voices because for the first time in a long time, the world is listening. So I will continue my efforts in fighting for my life, for the lives lost along the fight, and for the young Black lives that will come after me.\xe2\x80\x9d - @okdeon, photographer, model, and content creator. Head to our Pride Story Highlight to hear more from Deon.'

b'"Pride is love coming from different directions, crossing paths to connect and uplift individuals and the community. " - @zzdesign is a graphic artist and the creative mind behind our #Pride2020 identity. :raising_hands: Hear more from Zipeng in our Pride Story Highlight.'

b'Astrologer and queer activist, @chaninicholas, in her own words - \xe2\x80\x9cPride means that despite living in a world that largely invisiblizes, criminalizes, and pathologizes your existence, you find every way possible to love, celebrate, and revel in the beauty of yourself and your community.
